Root cause:
The bug was caused by the improper handling of user-generated content in the web application, which allowed for the possibility of Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. Specifically, the application was directly appending strings to the HTML without sanitization, enabling malicious scripts to be executed in the user's browser.

Code statements information:
The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```javascript
$("#debug").append(str + "\n");
$("#messages").append("<p>" + message.body + "</p>\n");
```
Reason:
The application directly appends user-generated content (the `str` and `message.body` variables) to the HTML without any sanitization, which allows for the execution of malicious scripts in the user's browser, leading to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```javascript
$("#debug").append(document.createTextNode(str + "\n"));
$("#messages").append(document.createTextNode("<p>" + message.body + "</p>\n"));
```
Reason:
By using `document.createTextNode()`, the code ensures that the user-generated content is treated as plain text rather than HTML. This prevents any embedded scripts from being executed, effectively mitigating the risk of XSS attacks.


